        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>search engine</strong> is a web-based system that crawls the internet, stores page data in a massive index, and uses ranking algorithms to deliver the most relevant results for any query. Google, Bing, Yahoo, DuckDuckGo, and Yandex are all search engines. Google dominates with 91.4% global market share, processing over 8.5 billion searches daily. Every SEO technique exists because of how search engines discover, evaluate, and rank content.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Google market share</div>
            <div class="tms-value">91.4% globally</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">General Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Traffic share (organic)</div>
            <div class="tms-value">53% of all web traffic</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Understanding how search engines work is the prerequisite for every SEO decision you make. Crawling, indexing, and ranking are not abstract concepts — they determine whether your pages are found, stored, and surfaced when your audience searches.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a search engine?</h2>
        <p>A search engine is a software system designed to search, index, and retrieve information from the web. When a user submits a query, the search engine scans its pre-built index — not the live web — and returns a ranked list of pages judged most relevant to that query.</p>
        <p>The term "search engine" covers several distinct products:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>General web search:</strong> Google, Bing, DuckDuckGo — index the open web broadly</li>
          <li><strong>Vertical search:</strong> Amazon (products), YouTube (video), LinkedIn (people/jobs) — index a specific domain</li>
          <li><strong>AI search:</strong> ChatGPT Search, Perplexity, Gemini — combine index retrieval with language model synthesis</li>
          <li><strong>Enterprise search:</strong> Elasticsearch, Algolia — index private internal content</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Market reality</div>
          <p>Google processes <strong>8.5 billion+ searches per day</strong> — roughly 99,000 queries per second. Bing holds 3.5% global share. For most English-language businesses, optimizing for Google effectively means optimizing for ~91% of search traffic.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why search engines matter for your business</h2>
        <p>Search engines are the primary intent-driven discovery channel. Unlike social media (interrupt) or email (pull), search users are actively looking for something — which creates purchase intent that other channels cannot replicate.</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Scale.</strong> Organic search drives 53% of all website traffic. No other single channel comes close to that share.</li>
          <li><strong>Intent signal.</strong> A user searching "plumber near me" is in buying mode. Social media browsers are not. Search captures demand; social media creates it.</li>
          <li><strong>Credibility transfer.</strong> Ranking organically on Google page one is an implicit third-party endorsement. Users trust organic results over ads by a wide margin.</li>
          <li><strong>Compounding returns.</strong> Unlike paid ads that stop when the budget runs out, a well-ranked page keeps delivering traffic for months or years. A page ranking #1 for a 10,000-search/month keyword earns roughly 2,700–3,100 visits per month indefinitely.</li>
          <li><strong>Cost structure.</strong> The marginal cost of organic traffic approaches zero over time. A blog post written once can generate leads for five years.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How a search engine works</h2>
        <p>Every major search engine operates on three sequential processes: crawling, indexing, and ranking. These run continuously in parallel as the web evolves.</p>

        <h3>1. Crawling</h3>
        <p>Search engines deploy automated bots — Googlebot, Bingbot — that follow hyperlinks across the web to discover pages. When a bot visits a page, it downloads the HTML, CSS, and JavaScript to understand content and find new links to follow. Crawl budget limits how many pages a bot processes per site per day; large sites with poor internal linking waste crawl budget on low-value pages.</p>

        <h3>2. Indexing</h3>
        <p>After crawling, the search engine processes each page and stores it in a massive database called the index. Not every crawled page gets indexed. Google skips pages with thin content, duplicate content, <code>noindex</code> directives, or slow server responses. A page that is not indexed cannot rank — making indexability a prerequisite for all other SEO work.</p>

        <h3>3. Ranking</h3>
        <p>When a user submits a query, the search engine queries its index and applies hundreds of ranking signals to order results. The primary signals include:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Relevance:</strong> Does the page's content match the query and its intent?</li>
          <li><strong>Authority:</strong> How many credible external sites link to this page?</li>
          <li><strong>Page experience:</strong> Does the page load fast, work on mobile, and not shift layout unexpectedly?</li>
          <li><strong>Freshness:</strong> For time-sensitive topics, how recently was the content updated?</li>
          <li><strong>E-E-A-T:</strong> Does the content demonstrate first-hand experience, expertise, authority, and trustworthiness?</li>
        </ul>

