        <h2 id="examples">Real search engine optimization examples</h2>
        <p>Here is how two businesses used search engine mechanics to generate measurable results.</p>

        <h3>Local dentist — local pack domination</h3>
        <p>A dental practice optimized their Google Business Profile, published 12 blog posts about common dental procedures, and earned local backlinks from the city directory and a dental association. Google's local algorithm evaluated relevance, proximity, and prominence, then ranked them in the local pack. Result: 40+ calls per month from organic search within 4 months.</p>

        <h3>Niche e-commerce — beating Amazon on specificity</h3>
        <p>A pet food brand published in-depth buyer's guides targeting long-tail queries Amazon's product pages could not satisfy (e.g., "best grain-free dog food for senior labs"). Within 6 months, they ranked above Amazon for 30+ product keywords and drove direct sales that bypassed marketplace fees.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Search engine vs social media — which to prioritize</h2>
        <p>The channel that deserves your investment depends on your audience's behavior and your content type.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Search engine advantages</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Captures existing demand (users who are already looking)</li>
              <li>Higher purchase intent — closer to the buy decision</li>
              <li>Traffic compounds over time without ongoing ad spend</li>
              <li>Works 24/7 without active management after ranking</li>
              <li>53% of all web traffic — largest single channel</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Social media advantages</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Creates demand for products people did not know they wanted</li>
              <li>Faster feedback loop — see results in days, not months</li>
              <li>Better for brand personality and community building</li>
              <li>Gen Z increasingly starts discovery on TikTok, Instagram</li>
              <li>Viral potential amplifies reach beyond your audience</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for optimizing for search engines</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Verify crawlability first.</strong> Use Google Search Console's URL Inspection tool to confirm Googlebot can reach and render your pages before investing in content.</li>
          <li><strong>Match content to search intent.</strong> Check the live SERP before writing. If the top results are how-to guides, write a how-to guide — not a product page.</li>
          <li><strong>Earn authoritative backlinks.</strong> Links from credible domains remain the strongest signal of authority. One link from a respected industry site outweighs 50 from low-quality directories.</li>
          <li><strong>Fix Core Web Vitals.</strong> Google's page experience signals — LCP, INP, CLS — directly affect ranking. Mobile load times above 3 seconds cause measurable ranking penalties.</li>
          <li><strong>Publish consistently.</strong> Google rewards sites that regularly add new, helpful content. A posting cadence of 2-4 quality articles per week is achievable and compounds over 12 months.</li>
          <li><strong>Use structured data.</strong> FAQ, HowTo, and Product schema help search engines extract information for rich results and AI Overviews, increasing visibility beyond the standard blue link.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — optimizing for the wrong engine</div>
          <p>Businesses sometimes invest in Bing or Yahoo optimization before maximizing Google. Because Bing's index is smaller and Google's signals (especially links and E-E-A-T) carry over partially, maximizing Google first almost always produces greater total organic traffic gain. Revisit Bing-specific tactics only after Google rankings are stable.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common search engine optimization mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Blocking Googlebot in robots.txt</strong> — accidentally disallows crawling and collapses rankings overnight</li>
          <li><strong>Duplicate content without canonicals</strong> — splits link equity and confuses the index about which URL to rank</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring mobile performance</strong> — Google uses mobile-first indexing; desktop optimization is secondary</li>
          <li><strong>Targeting keywords without checking intent</strong> — writing an informational article when the SERP shows product pages means you will not rank regardless of content quality</li>
          <li><strong>Chasing algorithm updates reactively</strong> — Google runs 4,000+ experiments per year; reacting to every tremor is costly and usually counterproductive</li>
          <li><strong>No internal linking structure</strong> — orphan pages are rarely crawled and carry zero PageRank from other pages on the site</li>
        </ul>

